The timer is not stopped when `OperationCanceledException` is thrown. This will result in inaccurate `responseTime` values on timeout, as the timer continues running until the method returns. Move `timer.Stop()` outside the try block or add it to the catch block:

```csharp
var timer = Stopwatch.StartNew();
try
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
    await clientSocket.ConnectAsync(endPoint, cts.Token).ConfigureAwait(false);
}
catch (OperationCanceledException)
{
    // 超时情况，responseTime保持为-1
}
finally
{
    timer.Stop();
    responseTime = (int)timer.Elapsed.TotalMilliseconds;
}
```

